## CRITICAL REQUIREMENTS - Enterprise Standards

### 1. Base Image Selection (CIS 4.1, 4.2)
**MUST:**
- Use official images from verified publishers only
- Pin to specific SHA256 digest (not just tags): `FROM image@sha256:...`
- Prefer distroless images (gcr.io/distroless/*) or minimal variants (alpine, slim)
- Use multi-stage builds to separate build dependencies from runtime
- Document base image selection rationale

**Example:**
```dockerfile
# Build stage with full toolchain
FROM python:3.11-slim@sha256:... AS builder

# Runtime stage with minimal image
FROM gcr.io/distroless/python3-debian11@sha256:... AS runtime
```

### 2. Security Hardening (NIST SP 800-190, OWASP)
**MUST:**
- Run as non-root user (UID > 10000) - CIS 4.1
- Drop all capabilities, add only required ones - CIS 5.25
- Set read-only root filesystem where possible - CIS 5.12
- Use COPY instead of ADD (prevents URL-based attacks) - CIS 4.9
- Never include secrets, credentials, or API keys in image - CIS 4.10
- Scan image for vulnerabilities (Trivy, Grype, Snyk)
- Minimize attack surface (remove shell, package managers in final stage)
- Use .dockerignore to exclude sensitive files - CIS 4.8

**Security Configuration:**
```dockerfile
# Create non-root user with no shell
RUN groupadd -r -g 10001 appgroup && \
    useradd -r -u 10001 -g appgroup -s /sbin/nologin -c "App user" appuser

# Drop all capabilities except required ones
USER 10001:10001

# Set security options in docker run:
# --cap-drop=ALL --cap-add=NET_BIND_SERVICE
# --security-opt=no-new-privileges:true
# --read-only --tmpfs /tmp:rw,noexec,nosuid
```

### 3. Build Optimization (Performance + Security)
**MUST:**
- Order layers from least to most frequently changing
- Combine RUN commands to minimize layers
- Use BuildKit for advanced caching: `# syntax=docker/dockerfile:1.4`
- Clean package manager caches in same RUN command
- Use .dockerignore extensively
- Leverage build cache mounts for dependencies
- Create SBOM during build for supply chain security

**BuildKit Example:**
```dockerfile
# syntax=docker/dockerfile:1.4

# Use cache mounts for package managers
RUN --mount=type=cache,target=/root/.cache/pip \
    --mount=type=bind,source=requirements.txt,target=requirements.txt \
    pip install -r requirements.txt
```

### 4. Runtime Configuration (Twelve-Factor App)
**MUST:**
- Set WORKDIR to non-root directory
- Define all environment variables with ENV
- Use ARG for build-time configuration
- Implement comprehensive HEALTHCHECK
- Use ENTRYPOINT for executable, CMD for default arguments
- EXPOSE only necessary ports
- Handle SIGTERM gracefully for zero-downtime deployments
- Configure proper logging to stdout/stderr

**Health Check Best Practice:**
```dockerfile
HEALTHCHECK --interval=30s --timeout=10s --start-period=30s --retries=3 \
  CMD ["/usr/bin/curl", "-f", "http://localhost:8000/health"] || exit 1
```

### 5. Metadata & Traceability (OCI Standard)
**MUST:**
- Include OCI-compliant labels - CIS 4.5
- Add build metadata (version, commit, timestamp)
- Include maintainer and documentation links
- Support vulnerability scanning metadata
- Include SBOM reference

**Required Labels:**
```dockerfile
LABEL org.opencontainers.image.title="Application Name"
LABEL org.opencontainers.image.description="Application Description"
LABEL org.opencontainers.image.version="{{ context.version | default('1.0.0') }}"
LABEL org.opencontainers.image.created="$(date -u +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ)"
LABEL org.opencontainers.image.source="https://github.com/org/repo"
LABEL org.opencontainers.image.licenses="MIT"
LABEL org.opencontainers.image.vendor="Your Organization"
LABEL com.example.security.scan="trivy"
```

### 6. Supply Chain Security
**MUST:**
- Verify checksums for downloaded artifacts
- Use content trust (Docker Content Trust / Notary)
- Generate SBOM (Software Bill of Materials)
- Sign images with Sigstore/Cosign
- Implement vulnerability scanning in CI/CD

### 7. Networking & Isolation
**MUST:**
- Use USER directive to drop privileges
- Consider using scratch or distroless for final stage
- Minimize exposed ports
- Configure container networking properly
- Use secrets management for sensitive data

